snippet.textDisplay:
COVID19 is not "mild", it is a virus, period, and whether it kills fewer people than other viruses is beside the point. COVID19 causes death in people who are immunocompromised. This is, of course, a reason for concern, as in South Africa alone, there are millions of people who are immunocompromised.

For example, people who have TB and/or HIV and don't adhere to their respective treatments (or those not on treatment), or people from poor communities (with poor water and sanitation systems) and a lack of nutritious food. Thus, COVID19 could be disastrous in South Africa.

Moreover, people who are infected without serious symptoms have the ability to infect other people who are immunocompromised. Needless to say, this can also be disastrous. In this view, COVID19 is, in fact, a major public health concern as the World Health Organization declares.

However, if you have not travelled overseas in the last week or more, and have not been in contact with people who did travel, then you have extremely low risk at this stage. Similarly, if you are otherwise healthy, your risk is low too, possibly even zero. Practice good hygiene. So you don't have a need to panic or stock up on any items, as the world is not ending, we just have a virus at hand that needs to be contained.

#COVID19
#DrMaarman

snippet.textDisplay:
The recommendation is to stay off airplanes, but not all airlines are waiving their change fees. United Airlines is claiming to have flexible booking this month, but the truth is that the flexible booking ONLY applies to tickets that people buy RIGHT NOW between March 3rd and 31st. People who bought tickets before March 3rd, but are scheduled to travel this month, are faced with the difficult decision of either losing hundreds of dollars to cover change fees, or getting on a plane. How does that make any sense?? If you bought your ticket in January, but are scheduled to travel in mid-March, you will be charged a change fee if you want to change/cancel your flight, but if you bought a ticket on March 3rd, you can reschedule for free. They are stealing loyal customers' money, and pressuring people to get on airplanes who don't feel comfortable getting on airplanes right now.




It infuriates me that they are claiming to care for the health and safety of their customers, and they are claiming that's the reason they've implemented this flexible booking policy. If they cared so much about health and safety, they would allow people who booked prior to March 3rd to also change their flights. At the same, United has said (in a Twitter comment I read) that they are doing flexible booking to encourage people to purchase tickets this month, who may be otherwise nervous to purchase tickets. So basically, they don't care about the people who already purchased tickets, because they already have those people's money. They only care to encourage new customers to also give United their money this month, because sales are down due to COVID-19.
